The Josephus problem is a theorhetical problem where a group of soldiers needed to decide who would go back to the base for help. They chose 2 numbers out of a hat, call them x and y. They would count x people from where the hat was to get to the starting point, and then count y from that person. Whoever was the person chosen after counting y was out, and then they would count y from him over and over til there was one left, that one needed to go

It implements something called a circular linked list to solve what is called the Josephus problem. There is a list of "Nodes" that both have data in them and have a reference to the next node creating a sequential list. This type of list is unique though because where a normal linked list has a beginning and an end (the end being where the last node references null or nothing), the circular linked list has a "tail" which is the "end" but references back to the first node...
